  "slides": [
    {
      "id": "deck-slide-0-1773417793730",
      "title": "Young Voters Overwhelmingly Backed Remain — Over 80% of 18-24s",
      "subtitle": "Weighted by Final BSA weight · N = 3,988 Respondents",
      "notes": "Among 18-24 year olds, 81% reported voting Remain vs just 18% Leave — a 63-point gap. This narrows steadily with age: by 65+, the balance reverses to 55% Leave vs 43% Remain. The age gradient is the single strongest demographic predictor of EU referendum vote in this dataset. Note: this is a split-sample question (versions A/B only), so ~44% of respondents are coded as missing. Chi-square is highly significant (p<0.001).",
      "analysisState": {
        "rowVars": [
          "EUVOTWHO"
        ],
        "colVar": "RAgeCat",
        "filters": [],
        "weightVar": "WtFactor"
      },
      "visualizationType": "table",
      "layoutMode": "focus",
      "cells": [],
      "sectionId": "deck-section-0-1773417793730",
      "createdAt": 1773417793730,
      "updatedAt": 1773417793730
    },
    {
      "id": "deck-slide-1-1773417793730",
      "title": "Party Lines Mirror the Leave-Remain Split Almost Exactly",
      "subtitle": "Weighted by Final BSA weight · N = 3,988 Respondents",
      "notes": "59% of Conservative identifiers voted Leave, while 68% of Labour and 83% of Liberal Democrat identifiers voted Remain. The alignment between party identity and referendum vote is striking — it suggests the Brexit question has been absorbed into existing partisan identity, or is reshaping it. Green Party supporters were also heavily Remain (72%). Among those with no party identification, Leave leads at 67%.",
      "analysisState": {
        "rowVars": [
          "EUVOTWHO"
        ],
        "colVar": "PartyId2",
        "filters": [],
        "weightVar": "WtFactor"
      },
      "visualizationType": "table",
      "layoutMode": "focus",
      "cells": [],
      "sectionId": "deck-section-0-1773417793730",
      "createdAt": 1773417793730,
      "updatedAt": 1773417793730
    },
    {
      "id": "deck-slide-2-1773417793730",
      "title": "Education Is a Sharp Dividing Line: 77% of Graduates Chose Remain",
      "subtitle": "Weighted by Final BSA weight · N = 3,988 Respondents",
      "notes": "The education gradient is nearly as strong as age. Among degree holders, 77% voted Remain. Among those with no qualifications, 69% voted Leave. The pattern is consistent across all intermediate levels — A-level holders split closer to Remain (59%), while those with O-levels or CSEs lean heavily Leave (61-62%). This echoes the widely reported diploma divide in the 2016 vote.",
      "analysisState": {
        "rowVars": [
          "EUVOTWHO"
        ],
        "colVar": "HEdQual",
        "filters": [],
        "weightVar": "WtFactor"
      },
      "visualizationType": "table",
      "layoutMode": "focus",
      "cells": [],
      "sectionId": "deck-section-0-1773417793730",
      "createdAt": 1773417793730,
      "updatedAt": 1773417793730
    },
    {
      "id": "deck-slide-3-1773417793730",
      "title": "Managerial Professionals Backed Remain; Routine Workers Backed Leave",
      "subtitle": "Weighted by Final BSA weight · N = 3,988 Respondents",
      "notes": "67% of those in managerial and professional occupations voted Remain. By contrast, 60% of semi-routine and routine workers, and 65% of lower supervisory/technical workers, voted Leave. Small employers split 59% Leave. The class gradient is real but less dramatic than age or education, suggesting that education may mediate much of the class effect.",
      "analysisState": {
        "rowVars": [
          "EUVOTWHO"
        ],
        "colVar": "RClassGp",
        "filters": [],
        "weightVar": "WtFactor"
      },
      "visualizationType": "table",
      "layoutMode": "focus",
      "cells": [],
      "sectionId": "deck-section-0-1773417793730",
      "createdAt": 1773417793730,
      "updatedAt": 1773417793730
    },
    {
      "id": "deck-slide-4-1773417793730",
      "title": "Leave Voters Are Strongly Authoritarian; Remain Voters Split Liberal",
      "subtitle": "Weighted by Final BSA weight · N = 3,988 Respondents",
      "notes": "69% of Leave voters score as authoritarian on the BSA libertarian-authoritarian scale, compared to just 29% of Remain voters. Conversely, 22% of Remain voters are libertarian vs only 2% of Leave voters. This confirms that the Leave-Remain divide is not just demographic but deeply values-based, aligning with attitudes on tradition, obedience, censorship, and sentencing.",
      "analysisState": {
        "rowVars": [
          "libauth2"
        ],
        "colVar": "EUVOTWHO",
        "filters": [],
        "weightVar": "WtFactor"
      },
      "visualizationType": "table",
      "layoutMode": "focus",
      "cells": [],
      "sectionId": "deck-section-0-1773417793730",
      "createdAt": 1773417793730,
      "updatedAt": 1773417793730
    },
    {
      "id": "deck-slide-5-1773417793730",
      "title": "Older Adults Are More Satisfied With the NHS Than Younger Ones",
      "subtitle": "Weighted by Final BSA weight · N = 3,988 Respondents",
      "notes": "Overall, 57% are satisfied with the NHS. Among 65+, 26% are very satisfied — roughly three times the rate of 18-24s. Younger respondents are more likely to sit in the neither category. Dissatisfaction is fairly even across ages.",
      "analysisState": {
        "rowVars": [
          "NHSSat"
        ],
        "colVar": "RAgeCat",
        "filters": [],
        "weightVar": "WtFactor"
      },
      "visualizationType": "table",
      "layoutMode": "focus",
      "cells": [],
      "sectionId": "deck-section-1-1773417793730",
      "createdAt": 1773417793730,
      "updatedAt": 1773417793730
    },
    {
      "id": "deck-slide-6-1773417793730",
      "title": "NHS Satisfaction Does Not Significantly Vary by Income",
      "subtitle": "Weighted by Final BSA weight · N = 3,988 Respondents",
      "notes": "Unlike many social attitudes, NHS satisfaction shows little variation across income quartiles. The overall satisfied/dissatisfied balance is remarkably similar, reflecting the universal nature of the NHS.",
      "analysisState": {
        "rowVars": [
          "NHSSat"
        ],
        "colVar": "HHIncQ",
        "filters": [],
        "weightVar": "WtFactor"
      },
      "visualizationType": "table",
      "layoutMode": "focus",
      "cells": [],
      "sectionId": "deck-section-1-1773417793730",
      "createdAt": 1773417793730,
      "updatedAt": 1773417793730
    },
    {
      "id": "deck-slide-7-1773417793730",
      "title": "Even 53% of Conservatives Want Higher Taxes for More Spending",
      "subtitle": "Weighted by Final BSA weight · N = 3,988 Respondents",
      "notes": "61% of the public overall wants higher taxes and more spending on health, education, and social benefits. Even among Conservatives it is a majority at 53%, showing cross-party support for public spending.",
      "analysisState": {
        "rowVars": [
          "TaxSpend"
        ],
        "colVar": "PartyId2",
        "filters": [],
        "weightVar": "WtFactor"
      },
      "visualizationType": "table",
      "layoutMode": "focus",
      "cells": [],
      "sectionId": "deck-section-1-1773417793730",
      "createdAt": 1773417793730,
      "updatedAt": 1773417793730
    },
    {
      "id": "deck-slide-8-1773417793730",
      "title": "Health Is the Top Spending Priority Across All Ages; Education Fades With Age",
      "subtitle": "Weighted by Final BSA weight · N = 3,988 Respondents",
      "notes": "Health is the clear top spending priority across the electorate, while education is a stronger concern for younger adults and fades with age. This question is split-sample, so the usable base is much smaller than the full survey.",
      "analysisState": {
        "rowVars": [
          "Spend1"
        ],
        "colVar": "RAgeCat",
        "filters": [],
        "weightVar": "WtFactor"
      },
      "visualizationType": "table",
      "layoutMode": "focus",
      "cells": [],
      "sectionId": "deck-section-1-1773417793730",
      "createdAt": 1773417793730,
      "updatedAt": 1773417793730
    },
    {
      "id": "deck-slide-9-1773417793730",
      "title": "Half of Non-Partisans 'Almost Never' Trust Government",
      "subtitle": "Weighted by Final BSA weight · N = 3,988 Respondents",
      "notes": "Trust in government is low overall. The sharpest contrast is between government-party supporters and respondents without party identification, among whom almost-never trust is extremely common.",
      "analysisState": {
        "rowVars": [
          "GovTrust"
        ],
        "colVar": "PartyId2",
        "filters": [],
        "weightVar": "WtFactor"
      },
      "visualizationType": "table",
      "layoutMode": "focus",
      "cells": [],
      "sectionId": "deck-section-2-1773417793730",
      "createdAt": 1773417793730,
      "updatedAt": 1773417793730
    },
    {
      "id": "deck-slide-10-1773417793730",
      "title": "Leave and Remain Voters Show Similar Levels of Government Distrust",
      "subtitle": "Weighted by Final BSA weight · N = 3,988 Respondents",
      "notes": "Contrary to a simple anti-establishment story, Leave and Remain voters show broadly similar trust profiles in 2017. Distrust is a general condition rather than a single-camp phenomenon.",
      "analysisState": {
        "rowVars": [
          "GovTrust"
        ],
        "colVar": "EUVOTWHO",
        "filters": [],
        "weightVar": "WtFactor"
      },
      "visualizationType": "table",
      "layoutMode": "focus",
      "cells": [],
      "sectionId": "deck-section-2-1773417793730",
      "createdAt": 1773417793730,
      "updatedAt": 1773417793730
    },
    {
      "id": "deck-slide-11-1773417793730",
      "title": "Education Has Little Effect on Government Trust",
      "subtitle": "Weighted by Final BSA weight · N = 3,988 Respondents",
      "notes": "Education strongly predicts Brexit attitudes and social values, but the effect on trust is much weaker. Distrust appears broadly distributed across educational groups.",
      "analysisState": {
        "rowVars": [
          "GovTrust"
        ],
        "colVar": "HEdQual",
        "filters": [],
        "weightVar": "WtFactor"
      },
      "visualizationType": "table",
      "layoutMode": "focus",
      "cells": [],
      "sectionId": "deck-section-2-1773417793730",
      "createdAt": 1773417793730,
      "updatedAt": 1773417793730
    },
    {
      "id": "deck-slide-12-1773417793730",
      "title": "NHS Satisfaction Crosses Party Lines Too — A Rare Area of Consensus",
      "subtitle": "Weighted by Final BSA weight · N = 3,988 Respondents",
      "notes": "While political attitudes are polarized on Brexit and values, NHS satisfaction is comparatively stable across the main party blocs, making it a useful contrast case for the deck close.",
      "analysisState": {
        "rowVars": [
          "NHSSat"
        ],
        "colVar": "PartyId2",
